WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:29.660
So, one sort of exercise, this is back when I was a decent teacher, but this is a long

00:00:29.660 --> 00:00:35.300
time ago, but one exercise that I did that maybe you can extract something from, I don't

00:00:35.300 --> 00:00:36.920
know, is I would teach the enthymeme.

00:00:37.560 --> 00:00:41.820
I just, like, here's what an enthymeme is, and I would teach the ubiquity of the enthymeme.

00:00:41.820 --> 00:00:47.140
I'm like, look, there are enthymemes, like, every third thing someone says is an enthymeme,

00:00:47.380 --> 00:00:52.400
and maybe even every other thing that someone says, and I would teach, like, the simple way

00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:57.000
of recognizing is the word because, like, you know, that's the easy way, like, such and

00:00:57.000 --> 00:00:59.260
such and such because of, like, you, there's an enthymeme.

00:00:59.720 --> 00:01:04.240
So, I would, what I would have them do is if they could point out, if someone in class

00:01:04.240 --> 00:01:07.580
said something, and it's all, the beginning of class is what it always happened.

00:01:07.620 --> 00:01:08.520
What did you guys think of the reading?

00:01:08.940 --> 00:01:10.000
It was really boring.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:13.640
It's like, ah, enthymeme, like, and a student would call out, there's an enthymeme.

00:01:13.740 --> 00:01:15.460
I didn't like it because it was boring.

00:01:15.980 --> 00:01:21.320
And, and then the student who had said, the student who had said the enthymeme has to now

00:01:21.320 --> 00:01:23.280
make it into a syllogism, right?

00:01:23.340 --> 00:01:25.180
Like, that was the, so that was the exercise.

00:01:25.260 --> 00:01:28.960
It's like, someone points out, like, oh, I heard an enthymeme, and then the student

00:01:28.960 --> 00:01:32.040
who said it has to now unpack it into an enthymeme.

00:01:32.140 --> 00:01:38.020
And what would happen if, if it's a comment of any interest at all, which is easy to come

00:01:38.020 --> 00:01:42.540
up with, is that, oh my gosh, you actually made an argument, even though you never thought

00:01:42.540 --> 00:01:43.120
of it as an argument.

00:01:43.120 --> 00:01:44.920
You just said, I thought the reading was boring.

00:01:45.040 --> 00:01:49.580
And it's like, well, there's an argument implicit as you unpack the enthymeme.

00:01:50.100 --> 00:01:55.260
And so, so by expanding it from the kind of the black box that is an enthymeme into something

00:01:55.260 --> 00:02:01.500
more formalized, like a syllogism, you realize, oh, there's a whole series of like seven steps,

00:02:02.020 --> 00:02:06.580
not just the Socrates mortal thing, but like, here's what I consider to be good.

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:08.320
Good count must be interesting.

00:02:08.620 --> 00:02:10.180
Interesting things are more informative.

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:14.200
And that, you know, like the whole series of steps, even just by saying the reading was

00:02:14.200 --> 00:02:18.280
boring, that you unpack and they go like, oh my God, I didn't realize there was a whole

00:02:18.280 --> 00:02:19.280
argument in there.

00:02:19.340 --> 00:02:21.720
And I'm like, yeah, that's how arguments work.

00:02:21.780 --> 00:02:25.160
They, you know, they work in this truncated form by not telling you what they are.

00:02:25.260 --> 00:02:28.720
So that was a way into, I wasn't explicitly teaching logos.

00:02:29.500 --> 00:02:35.720
I was really just teaching them to recognize the recurrence of enthymematic thinking in everyday

00:02:35.720 --> 00:02:36.960
kind of relance.

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:39.740
But it was an exercise that I think was pretty useful.

00:02:39.740 --> 00:02:42.580
Like they, they got good at like recognizing it.

00:02:42.660 --> 00:02:47.120
We got to a point where we had to call a moratorium because it was like, really, every third sentence

00:02:47.120 --> 00:02:48.220
wasn't an enthymeme.

00:02:48.920 --> 00:02:52.900
You know, like, okay, enthymeme in this, enthymeme, we didn't have time to do anything else.

00:02:53.540 --> 00:02:53.980
Right.

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:55.620
Well, imagine, yeah.

00:02:56.260 --> 00:02:57.260
I love that.

00:02:57.420 --> 00:03:02.220
I mean, and that's, that plays into the way that I want to think about all of these rhetorical

00:03:02.220 --> 00:03:08.900
concepts is really emphasize their inventive power and not treat, you know, logos as the,

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:14.120
you know, quality checking sort of thing, which ends up being totally paralyzing for students.

00:03:14.240 --> 00:03:16.300
Because they go like, I can't, everything I write is wrong.

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:17.340
It's this or that fallacy.

00:03:17.420 --> 00:03:19.060
So I can't write anything.

00:03:19.540 --> 00:03:22.960
So, and then, I mean, you, what you could, what you could do with that is as you unpack

00:03:22.960 --> 00:03:27.780
the enthymeme, you could be pointing out the various associational structures between the

00:03:27.780 --> 00:03:30.120
six points that they had presumed.

00:03:30.120 --> 00:03:30.380
Right.

00:03:30.420 --> 00:03:33.280
Like, so, ah, that's a causal argument.

00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:35.080
Ah, that's an argument from origin.

00:03:35.300 --> 00:03:36.540
Ah, that's an, you know what I mean?

00:03:36.540 --> 00:03:40.880
Like, so the, the, the things that are linking them and you try, try it in a classroom and

00:03:40.880 --> 00:03:41.580
shit's going to come out.

00:03:41.620 --> 00:03:44.900
I mean, it's, it's a really easy exercise to get them thinking.

00:03:44.900 --> 00:03:48.100
And they, I mean, it just rolled from the couple of times that I did it.

00:03:48.100 --> 00:03:50.380
Like it just rolled, it was super easy to do.

00:03:50.620 --> 00:03:54.620
And, and it just like, you'll take up whole class periods where you'll just end up filling,

00:03:54.800 --> 00:03:55.900
filling and rolling.

00:03:56.360 --> 00:04:00.400
And as you're unpacking them, and if you could come up with, like, I wasn't really paying

00:04:00.400 --> 00:04:02.840
attention to what are the means of the association.

00:04:02.840 --> 00:04:07.300
I simply wanted them to recognize the truncated argument and to elongate it.

00:04:07.300 --> 00:04:11.980
It's like, oh my God, you actually just wrote a paper in your comment in response to the

00:04:11.980 --> 00:04:13.980
reading and you didn't realize it, right?

00:04:14.020 --> 00:04:18.580
Like you now have an argument and reasons that you didn't realize that you'd, you'd

00:04:18.580 --> 00:04:19.440
had, right?

00:04:31.280 --> 00:04:35.760
This also, this reminds me a little bit of some of our conversations about taste, because

00:04:35.760 --> 00:04:39.560
you're saying like the initial enthymeme is usually like, well, I didn't like this, you

00:04:39.560 --> 00:04:43.660
know, and how many arguments are basically rooted initially in a, in a taste.

00:04:44.020 --> 00:04:45.280
You know, a question of taste.

00:04:45.280 --> 00:04:51.340
And it's like, you know, there's obviously then a structure to taste and to preference.

00:04:51.760 --> 00:04:55.140
And like, you know, you would think of taste as being associated with pathos, right?

00:04:55.140 --> 00:04:57.600
Or an emotional sort of relation to the text.

00:04:57.600 --> 00:05:02.420
But then clearly it's also structured by a bunch of other relationships that you have.

00:05:02.420 --> 00:05:06.940
Like, you know, so I, I think that's, that's also a good way to, to get them.

00:05:07.020 --> 00:05:11.640
Cause a lot of students can't get past the, I don't like this or I like this thing.

00:05:11.640 --> 00:05:11.960
Right.

00:05:11.960 --> 00:05:13.880
It's like you, you, what you want them to do is, yeah.

00:05:13.880 --> 00:05:17.440
I think that too is going to disrupt the, the supposedly subjective position of the, of

00:05:17.440 --> 00:05:17.820
the taste.

00:05:17.820 --> 00:05:18.240
That's right.

00:05:18.340 --> 00:05:18.520
Right.

00:05:18.600 --> 00:05:22.940
As soon as you unpack the enthymeme, it's like suddenly you find the general principles

00:05:22.940 --> 00:05:24.400
that you're expecting everyone else.

00:05:24.400 --> 00:05:24.700
Right.

00:05:24.900 --> 00:05:25.140
Right.

00:05:25.140 --> 00:05:26.520
We're into Kant's third critique.

00:05:26.860 --> 00:05:27.180
Right.

00:05:27.380 --> 00:05:27.620
Yeah.

00:05:27.860 --> 00:05:28.000
Yeah.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:32.100
The other thing with the enthymeme too is like the, the, what you talked about the

00:05:32.100 --> 00:05:36.260
enthymeme game is like it, you have to call a moratorium on it because it just expounds

00:05:36.260 --> 00:05:42.080
it's like, yeah, like, I mean, this is the same, you, you get to the same conclusion when

00:05:42.080 --> 00:05:46.040
you start analyzing, you know, the syllogism is that as soon as you start having to make

00:05:46.040 --> 00:05:52.320
the steps in between the gaps and propositions that will proliferate itself, that proliferates

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:53.100
itself infinitely.

00:05:53.100 --> 00:05:58.220
